#include "gpio.h"
#include "pyprintf.h"

//Function to turn on/off a selected pin of PMODB
void write_gpio(unsigned int pin, unsigned int val){
    if (val > 1){
        pyprintf("pin value must be 0 or 1");
    }
    gpio pin_out = gpio_open(pin);
    gpio_set_direction(pin_out, GPIO_OUT);
    gpio_write(pin_out, val);
}

//Function to read the value of a selected pin of PMODB
unsigned int read_gpio(unsigned int pin){
    gpio pin_in = gpio_open(pin);
    gpio_set_direction(pin_in, GPIO_IN);
    return gpio_read(pin_in);
}

2. Write a Python3 cell that emulates a PWM (for a chosen frequency and duty cycle) on one of the PMOD GPIO pins.¶

For example, PMODB PIN3 needs to turn on for duty_cycle percent of the square wave frequency and off for the rest of the square wave. It may not be possible to achieve exactly 0% or 100% so be sure to add necessary code for those corner cases.

In [9]:
# Pulse Width Modulation
def runPWM(color, f, dc):
    T = 1/f
    maxCnt = int(5 / T) # number of period for 20 sec
        
    rgb = {'r': [1,0,0],
           'g': [0,1,0],
           'b': [0,0,1]
          }
    #print(rgb[color][0])
    r, g, b = rgb[color][0], rgb[color][1], rgb[color][2]
    print(r, g, b, T, maxCnt, int(maxCnt*T))
        
    cnt = 0
    while (cnt<maxCnt):
        cnt+=1
        if r == 1:
            write_gpio(3, 1)
            time.sleep(T * dc)
            write_gpio(3, 0)
            time.sleep(T * (1-dc))
    
        if g == 1:
            write_gpio(2, 1)
            time.sleep(T * dc)
            write_gpio(2, 0)
            time.sleep(T * (1-dc))
            
        if b == 1:
            write_gpio(1, 1)
            time.sleep(T * dc)
            write_gpio(1, 0)
            time.sleep(T * (1-dc))
    
    
    print('done, LED are off...')
    setAllOff()

4. Achieve the visually perceived 100%, 75%, 50% and 25% of full LED brightness by adjusting the duty cycle;¶

5. Varying the duty cycles and approximate the corresponding LED brightness (in the unit of %).¶

To the end, plot and explain the approximate relationship of % brightness versus duty cycle. While working on this task, feel free to check out the $\textbf{Weber-Fechner law}$. For light perception, this law describe the observation that the our eyes perceive light in a non-linear way.

Weber-Fechner law (From Bard AI)¶

In essence, the Weber-Fechner law states that the Just Noticeable Difference ($\textbf{JND}$), the smallest change in a stimulus that can be perceived, is proportional to the original stimulus intensity. $\textbf{This means that for a larger initial stimulus, a bigger change is needed to perceive a difference.}$

Human eyes most sensitively respond to green color, peaking around 555nm. (https://colors.dopely.top/inside-colors/the-most-visible-colors-for-human-eyes/). Therefore, the following trials went with green.¶

try various dc, e.g., dc = 0.05, 0.2, 0.5, and 0.99¶

You’ll want to use $\textbf{asyncio}$ for this part.

• Start the code and blink the LED’s $\textbf{red channel in intervals of 1 second (i.e. 1 second on, 1 second off)}$

• When $\textbf{buttons 0, 1, or 2}$ are pushed, the LED will change color from $\textbf{Red, to Green, to Blue.}$

• When $\textbf{button 3}$ is pushed, the $\textbf{LED will stop blinking}$.

• Your video should demonstrate how each button change to each of the (4) colors.

#asyncio is often a perfect fit for IO-bound and high-level structured network code 
import asyncio
cond = True
start = 0

async def runPWMLED(f, dc):
    T = 1/f
    
    global cond, start
    while cond:
        if start == 0:      # blinking Red led as initial condition
            write_gpio(3, 1)
            await asyncio.sleep(T * dc)
            write_gpio(3, 0)
            await asyncio.sleep(T * (1-dc))
    
        if start == 1:      # blinking green led
            write_gpio(2, 1)
            await asyncio.sleep(T * dc)
            write_gpio(2, 0)
            await asyncio.sleep(T * (1-dc))
            
        if start == 2:      # blinking blue led
            write_gpio(1, 1)
            await asyncio.sleep(T * dc)
            write_gpio(1, 0)
            await asyncio.sleep(T * (1-dc))
    
async def get_btns(_loop):
    global cond, start
    while cond:
        await asyncio.sleep(0.01)
        #print('cond')
        if btns.read() == 1: # blinking Red led
            start = 0
            await asyncio.sleep(0.3)
            print("pressing BTN0, blinking Red led...")
        
        elif btns.read() == 2: # blinking green led
            start = 1
            await asyncio.sleep(0.3)
            print("pressing BTN1, blinking Green led...")
   
        elif btns.read() == 4: # blinking blue led
            start = 2
            await asyncio.sleep(0.3)
            print("pressing BTN2, blinking Blue led...")
    
        elif btns.read() == 8: #stop blinking
            cond = False
            await asyncio.sleep(0.3)
            print("pressing BTN3, stop blinking")
            _loop.stop()

loop = asyncio.new_event_loop()    # Create and return a new event loop object.

f, dc = 1/2, 0.2                   # 2 second period -> 0.5 Hz, 20% dutcy cycle
loop.create_task(runPWMLED(f, dc)) # blink the LED’s  in intervals of 1 second (i.e. 1 second on, 1 second off)
 
loop.create_task(get_btns(loop))
loop.run_forever()
loop.close()
